article.description: Mike James hit a 16-foot jumper with 1.8 seconds left to give the Boston Celtics a 93-91 victory Friday night over the Memphis Grizzlies .
article.headline: Boston 93, Memphis 91

images.name: Pierce Paul 031031 195x262
images.caption: Paul Pierce will face a lot of defensive pressure this season.

article.linkText: Boston's Baker leads Celtics over Grizz 93-91
article.story:
MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- Mike James hit a 16-foot jumper with 1.8 seconds left to give the Boston Celtics a 93-91 victory Friday night over the Memphis Grizzlies. Memphis tied its opener at 91 when Pau Gasol hit a pair of free throws with 10.4 seconds to go. He was fouled by Paul Pierce, who had 10 of his 23 points in the final period. Vin Baker led Boston with 24 points and eight rebounds. James had 16 points and six assists. Memphis was led by Stromile Swift with 18 points, while Gasol had 16 points and 10 rebounds. But he was unable to get off a shot after taking the inbound pass 20 feet from the basket on the Grizzlies' final possession. Jason Williams had 13 points and seven assists but was 3-of-11 from the field for the Grizzlies. Mike Miller added 10 points for Memphis. The Celtics took their first lead since early in the opening quarter at 66-65 with 1:09 left in the third period on a dunk by Baker. Boston began the final period with a 70-69 lead. The Celtics started a 12-2 run less than a minute later that resulted in their biggest lead, 90-80, with just over four minutes left. The Grizzlies held a 47-44 lead at halftime.

Game notes
Boston's Jumaine Jones was sidelined with a strained bilateral hamstring. ... The Grizzlies have lost five straight to Boston and have not beaten the Celtics since moving to Memphis. ... The Grizzlies have won a season opener only twice in the franchise history and never in Memphis. ... After moving to Memphis in 2001, the Grizzlies opened the first season in their new home at 0-8 and the second at 0-13. ... Celtics coach Jim O'Brien got his first technical of the season when he argued a no-call in the first quarter as Bo Outlaw guarded Walter McCarty. ... Boston's Eric Williams left the game with an injured right knee.
